<DOC><DOCNO> AP880627-0040 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-88 0410EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     06-27 0282</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0293</SECOND><HEAD>Flood Death Toll Rises To 17</HEAD><DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eight more people have died inflood-related accidents in Bangladesh, raising the death toll inthe past week to at least 17, officials and press reports saidtoday.   Seven fishermen drowned after being swept into the Bay of Bengalearly Sunday when an embankment crumbled under the pressure offlood waters, officials in the port city of Chittagong said.   Another person was killed Sunday when a mudslide buried hishouse in the Chittagong Hill Tracts, the officials said, speakingon condition of anonymity.   Nine people died in floods earlier last week.   Officials in Dhaka said rail and road links between the capitaland the northern Sylhet and Sunamganj districts _ hardest hit bythe floods _ have been disrupted by the swirling waters.   All trains running between Sylhet and Dhaka have been canceled,they added.   Ittefaq, a Bengali-language newspaper, said floods have strandedmore than 500,000 people in the remote areas of northern Netrokonadistrict.   Rescue teams have been evacuating the people to governmentshelters, mostly by boat, the newspaper said.   Thousands of homes have been destroyed in the region, Ittefaqreported.   Most of the victims are poor people who live and farm inlow-lying areas that are flooded when Bangladesh's many riversoverflow during the annual monsoon rains.   Earlier this month, at least 25 people died in the first spateof monsoon-related flooding, according to official count.Unofficial reports put the figure at 50.   More than 1,200 people were killed last year in devastatingfloods that destroyed crops the government said could have yield3.4 million tons of rice for this impoverished, food-importingnation of 105 million people.</TEXT></DOC>